Day 10 — Properties, Metadata, and AQL Searching
Properties
Properties are key-value pairs attached to artifacts. They are the foundation of searchability and automation in Artifactory.

artifact.jar
  ├── build.number = 42
  ├── env = prod
  ├── git.commit = abc123
  ├── approved.by = john.doe
  └── status = ready-for-deploy

Properties can be:

Set during upload by CI/CD
Added/modified by release processes
Used in Xray policies
Used as routing/filtering criteria
Property Sets
Pre-defined sets of allowed property values for governance — ensures consistent property values across teams.

AQL (Artifactory Query Language)
A domain-specific query language for searching artifacts by any combination of:

Repository, path, filename
File size, date
Custom properties
Build info
Statistics (download count, last downloaded)

AQL Structure:
{domain}.find({criteria})
  .include({fields})
  .sort({field})
  .limit({n})

Example — find all artifacts deployed from build #42:
items.find({
  "@build.number": "42",
  "repo": {"$match": "*-local"}
})
.include("name", "repo", "path", "created", "@build.number")

Example — find artifacts not downloaded in 90 days:
items.find({
  "type": "file",
  "repo": "libs-release-local",
  "stat.downloaded": {"$before": "90d"}
})

Smart Repositories (Virtual with Default Deployment Target)
Virtual repos can have a configured local repo as the default deployment target — so your build tool points to one virtual URL for both reads and writes.
